<p id="Par23" class="p">Here, we propose a simple model to estimate the critical oil-to-nanoparticle ratio 
 <italic class="italic">k</italic>
 <sup class="sup">*</sup> of the colloidal suspension to acquire ball-like supraparticles. Illustration Fig. 
 <xref rid="Fig2" ref-type="fig" class="xref">2d</xref> shows a spherical supraparticle (SP) submerged in a spherical-cap oil drop. The maximum size of the supraparticle is the height of the oil drop 
 <italic class="italic">H</italic>. From a simple geometrical consideration, we obtain the volume of the spherical supraparticle
 <disp-formula id="Equ1" class="disp-formula">
  <label class="label">1</label>
  <alternatives class="alternatives">
   <tex-math id="M3" class="tex-math">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$V_{{\mathrm{SP}}} = \frac{1}{6}\pi H^3,$$\end{document}</tex-math>
   <math id="M4" display="block" class="math">
    <msub class="msub">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">V</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">SP</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mo class="mo">=</mo>
    <mfrac class="mfrac">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">1</mn>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">6</mn>
     </mrow>
    </mfrac>
    <mi class="mi">π</mi>
    <msup class="msup">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">H</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">3</mn>
     </mrow>
    </msup>
    <mo class="mo">,</mo>
   </math>
   <graphic xlink:href="41467_2019_8385_Article_Equ1.gif" position="anchor" class="graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
  </alternatives>
 </disp-formula>and the volume of the oil drop (OD)
 <disp-formula id="Equ2" class="disp-formula">
  <label class="label">2</label>
  <alternatives class="alternatives">
   <tex-math id="M5" class="tex-math">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$V_{{\mathrm{OD}}} = \frac{1}{6}\pi H^3\left[ {1 + 3\,{\mathrm{cot}}^2\left( {\frac{{\theta _{{\mathrm{oil}}}}}{2}} \right)} \right],$$\end{document}</tex-math>
   <math id="M6" display="block" class="math">
    <msub class="msub">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">V</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">OD</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mo class="mo">=</mo>
    <mfrac class="mfrac">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">1</mn>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">6</mn>
     </mrow>
    </mfrac>
    <mi class="mi">π</mi>
    <msup class="msup">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">H</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">3</mn>
     </mrow>
    </msup>
    <mfenced close="]" open="[" separators="" class="mfenced">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">1</mn>
      <mo class="mo">+</mo>
      <mn class="mn">3</mn>
      <mspace width="0.3em" class="mspace"/>
      <msup class="msup">
       <mrow class="mrow">
        <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">cot</mi>
       </mrow>
       <mrow class="mrow">
        <mn class="mn">2</mn>
       </mrow>
      </msup>
      <mfenced close=")" open="(" separators="" class="mfenced">
       <mrow class="mrow">
        <mfrac class="mfrac">
         <mrow class="mrow">
          <msub class="msub">
           <mrow class="mrow">
            <mi class="mi">θ</mi>
           </mrow>
           <mrow class="mrow">
            <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">oil</mi>
           </mrow>
          </msub>
         </mrow>
         <mrow class="mrow">
          <mn class="mn">2</mn>
         </mrow>
        </mfrac>
       </mrow>
      </mfenced>
     </mrow>
    </mfenced>
    <mo class="mo">,</mo>
   </math>
   <graphic xlink:href="41467_2019_8385_Article_Equ2.gif" position="anchor" class="graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
  </alternatives>
 </disp-formula>with the oil contact angle 
 <italic class="italic">θ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">oil</sub>. The volume of the oil is estimated as
 <disp-formula id="Equ3" class="disp-formula">
  <label class="label">3</label>
  <alternatives class="alternatives">
   <tex-math id="M7" class="tex-math">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$V_{{\mathrm{oil}}} = V_{{\mathrm{OD}}} - V_{{\mathrm{SP}}},$$\end{document}</tex-math>
   <math id="M8" display="block" class="math">
    <msub class="msub">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">V</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">oil</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mo class="mo">=</mo>
    <msub class="msub">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">V</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">OD</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mo class="mo">-</mo>
    <msub class="msub">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">V</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">SP</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mo class="mo">,</mo>
   </math>
   <graphic xlink:href="41467_2019_8385_Article_Equ3.gif" position="anchor" class="graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
  </alternatives>
 </disp-formula>while the total volume of nanoparticles (NPs) is given by
 <disp-formula id="Equ4" class="disp-formula">
  <label class="label">4</label>
  <alternatives class="alternatives">
   <tex-math id="M9" class="tex-math">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$V_{{\mathrm{NPs}}} = V_{{\mathrm{SP}}}(1 - \phi ),$$\end{document}</tex-math>
   <math id="M10" display="block" class="math">
    <msub class="msub">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">V</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">NPs</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mo class="mo">=</mo>
    <msub class="msub">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">V</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">SP</mi>
     </mrow>
    </msub>
    <mrow class="mrow">
     <mo class="mo">(</mo>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">1</mn>
      <mo class="mo">-</mo>
      <mi class="mi">ϕ</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mo class="mo">)</mo>
    </mrow>
    <mo class="mo">,</mo>
   </math>
   <graphic xlink:href="41467_2019_8385_Article_Equ4.gif" position="anchor" class="graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
  </alternatives>
 </disp-formula>where 
 <italic class="italic">ϕ</italic> is the porosity of the supraparticle. Thus, we obtain an estimation of the initial oil-to-nanoparticles ratio 
 <italic class="italic">k</italic>
 <sup class="sup">*</sup> to have spherical supraparticles, namely
 <disp-formula id="Equ5" class="disp-formula">
  <label class="label">5</label>
  <alternatives class="alternatives">
   <tex-math id="M11" class="tex-math">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal} \usepackage{amsmath} \usepackage{wasysym} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{upgreek} \setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt} \begin{document}$$k^ \ast = \frac{3}{{1 - \phi }}{\mathrm{cot}}^2\frac{{\theta _{{\mathrm{oil}}}}}{2},$$\end{document}</tex-math>
   <math id="M12" display="block" class="math">
    <msup class="msup">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi class="mi">k</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mo class="mo">*</mo>
     </mrow>
    </msup>
    <mo class="mo">=</mo>
    <mfrac class="mfrac">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">3</mn>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">1</mn>
      <mo class="mo">-</mo>
      <mi class="mi">ϕ</mi>
     </mrow>
    </mfrac>
    <msup class="msup">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">cot</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">2</mn>
     </mrow>
    </msup>
    <mfrac class="mfrac">
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <msub class="msub">
       <mrow class="mrow">
        <mi class="mi">θ</mi>
       </mrow>
       <mrow class="mrow">
        <mi mathvariant="normal" class="mi">oil</mi>
       </mrow>
      </msub>
     </mrow>
     <mrow class="mrow">
      <mn class="mn">2</mn>
     </mrow>
    </mfrac>
    <mo class="mo">,</mo>
   </math>
   <graphic xlink:href="41467_2019_8385_Article_Equ5.gif" position="anchor" class="graphic" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink"/>
  </alternatives>
 </disp-formula>which only depends on the oil contact angle 
 <italic class="italic">θ</italic>
 <sub class="sub">oil</sub> and the supraparticle porosity 
 <italic class="italic">ϕ</italic> and is independent of the drop size. In Eq. (
 <xref rid="Equ3" ref-type="" class="xref">3</xref>), we use 
 <italic class="italic">V</italic>
 <sub class="sub">SP</sub> instead of 
 <italic class="italic">V</italic>
 <sub class="sub">NPs</sub>, because we assume that the residual water fills the porous structure.
</p>
